com.vector.cfg.util.math

Class MBigDecimal

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Number
      • java.math.BigDecimal
        • com.vector.cfg.util.math.MBigDecimal
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<java.math.BigDecimal>

    @PublishedApi(value=ADDITIONS_ALLOWED)
public class MBigDecimal
extends java.math.BigDecimal
    A MBigDecimal provides the same functionality as BigDecimal, but could also have the following values:
    • NaN
    • INF
    • -INF

    (c) Copyright Vctr Informatik GmbH. All Rights Reserved.

      • compareTo

        @PublishedMethod
public final int compareTo(java.math.BigDecimal val)
        Compares two MBigDecimal objects numerically. There are two ways in which comparisons performed by this method differ from those performed by the Java language numerical comparison operators (<, <=, ==, >=, >) when applied to primitive double values:
        • MBigDecimal.NaN is considered by this method to be equal to itself and greater than all other MBigDecimal values (including MBigDecimal.POSITIVE_INFINITY).
        • 0.0d is considered by this method to be greater than -0.0d.
        This ensures that the natural ordering of MBigDecimal objects imposed by this method is consistent with equals.
        Specified by:
        compareTo in interface java.lang.Comparable<java.math.BigDecimal>
        Overrides:
        compareTo in class java.math.BigDecimal
        Parameters:
        val - MBigDecimal to which this BigDecimal is to be compared.
        Returns:
        -1, 0, or 1 as this MBigDecimal is numerically less than, equal to, or greater than val.

        public final int hashCode()

        Note: MBigDecimal.hashCode() doesn't require special handling for NaN, INF and -INF, because they are special values but also valid BigDecimal values. So they have a defined hashcode values from the base implementation.

      • valueOf

        @PublishedMethod
public static MBigDecimal valueOf(double val)
        Translates a double into a MBigDecimal, using the double's canonical string representation provided by the Double.toString(double) method.

        Note: This is generally the preferred way to convert a double (or float) into a BigDecimal, as the value returned is equal to that resulting from constructing a BigDecimal from the result of using Double.toString(double).

        Parameters:
        val - double to convert to a BigDecimal.
        Returns:
        a BigDecimal whose value is equal to or approximately equal to the value of val.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NumberFormatException - if val is infinite or NaN.

      • valueOf

        @PublishedMethod
public static MBigDecimal valueOf(double val,
                                                    java.math.MathContext mc)
        Translates a double into a BigDecimal, with rounding according to the context settings. The scale of the BigDecimal is the smallest value such that (10scale × val) is an integer.

        The results of this constructor can be somewhat unpredictable and its use is generally not recommended; see the notes under the #BigDecimal(double) constructor.

        Parameters:
        val - double value to be converted to BigDecimal.
        mc - the context to use.
        Throws:
        java.lang.ArithmeticException - if the result is inexact but the RoundingMode is UNNECESSARY.
        java.lang.NumberFormatException - if val is infinite or NaN.
